However, let's briefly look back. "What's inside, exactly?" It seems no one has asked.
At the top is an ESP32 camera board with a fish-eye lens camera, and an infrared LED I took off from a Raspberry Pi camera.
That plastic box has an unusual shape because the side panels of the nest box can rotate. It was like this when I bought it, and it can't be modified, so I have to design around this condition.
Since there is no power source in the garden, the entire setup is powered by a solar panel and an 18650 lithium-ion battery with a capacity of 2600 mAh.
I didn't take photos of the battery or charger, but this is a photo of the solar panel.
The gray box attached to the side of the nest box contains the batteries.
After being fully charged, it can operate for about 4 hours.
I call this a "special feature." This way, the birds also have some private space.
